### Abstract Classes in C#

An abstract class is a class that cannot be instantiated. It serves as a base for other classes and can contain both abstract and concrete members.

### Declaring Abstract Classes

```csharp
public abstract class Shape
{
    // Abstract method (no implementation)
    public abstract double GetArea();

    // Concrete method (with implementation)
    public void Display()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"Area: {GetArea():F2}");
    }

    // Abstract property
    public abstract string Name { get; }
}
```

### Implementing Abstract Class

```csharp
public class Circle : Shape
{
    public double Radius { get; }

    public Circle(double radius) => Radius = radius;

    public override double GetArea() => Math.PI * Radius * Radius;

    public override string Name => "Circle";
}
```

### Abstract Class Features

| Feature | Can Have |
|---------|----------|
| Abstract methods | Yes (no body) |
| Concrete methods | Yes (with body) |
| Fields | Yes |
| Properties | Yes (abstract or concrete) |
| Constructors | Yes (called from derived) |
| Static members | Yes |

### Abstract vs Interface

| Aspect | Abstract Class | Interface |
|--------|---------------|-----------|
| Instantiation | Cannot instantiate | Cannot instantiate |
| Members | Methods, fields, properties | Methods, properties, events |
| Implementation | Can have implementation | No implementation (until C# 8) |
| Inheritance | Single inheritance | Multiple implementation |
| Fields | Can have fields | Cannot have fields |
| Constructors | Can have constructors | Cannot have constructors |
| Access modifiers | All access modifiers | Public by default |

### Abstract Properties

```csharp
public abstract class Product
{
    public abstract string Name { get; }
    public abstract decimal Price { get; }
    public abstract string GetDescription();
}

public class Book : Product
{
    public override string Name { get; }
    public override decimal Price { get; }

    public Book(string name, decimal price)
    {
        Name = name;
        Price = price;
    }

    public override string GetDescription() => $"Book: {Name} - {Price:C}";
}
```

### When to Use Abstract Classes

```
- Related classes share common functionality
- You want to provide default behavior while forcing some implementations
- Classes are conceptually related (is-a relationship)
- You need fields or constructors
```

> **Key Point:** Abstract classes cannot be instantiated directly. They combine the benefits of inheritance with the requirement that certain methods must be implemented. Use abstract classes for closely related objects with shared code. Use interfaces for unrelated objects that share capabilities.

### Abstract Methods Rules

| Rule | Description |
|------|-------------|
| No body | Abstract methods have no implementation `{ }` |
| Must override | Derived classes MUST implement |
| Virtual implicitly | Abstract methods are implicitly virtual |
| Cannot be static | Abstract methods must be instance methods |
| Cannot be private | Must be accessible to derived classes |

codeExample:
using System;

public abstract class Payment
{
    public decimal Amount { get; set; }
    public abstract void ProcessPayment();
    public void PrintReceipt() => Console.WriteLine($"Paid: {Amount:C}");
}

public class CreditCardPayment : Payment
{
    public override void ProcessPayment()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"Processing credit card payment of {Amount:C}");
    }
}

public class PayPalPayment : Payment
{
    public override void ProcessPayment()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"Processing PayPal payment of {Amount:C}");
    }
}

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        Payment[] payments = { new CreditCardPayment { Amount = 50 }, new PayPalPayment { Amount = 75 } };
        foreach (var p in payments)
        {
            p.ProcessPayment();
            p.PrintReceipt();
        }
    }
}
